Chapter One
Koren
Itanian time, 4:30 a.m. Koren hated getting up so early. Mainly because he was responsible for waking up the rest of the platoon. He silently got out of bed, put on his combat suit, fastened his assault vest, packed up his things from the cabinet, and carefully picked up a small special box. He shouldered his rifle and hung his helmet on a small hook on his belt. The helmet was equipped with a full set of gear, including a respirator, goggles, and other necessary items. After checking his ammunition bag, he quietly left the barracks, his boots crunching on the muddy and icy ground.
He took out a lighter from his jacket pocket and a cigarette from another pocket. After lighting the cigarette, he took a light puff and then opened the door. In the past week, he had to think of every possible way to wake up his subordinates. He no longer used the preset alarm clock, because half the time it didn't go off, and all that could be heard from the speaker was a faint static.
"Time to wake them up?" Koren turned around and saw Lieutenant Nemici approaching.
"Yes." Kollen replied.
"What method are you planning to use this time?"
Before Kollen could answer, the door opened, and Harris, Cress, and a few others hurried out, already dressed and ready.
"Good morning," Cress said.
"What woke you up?" Kollen asked.
"First of all, we really don't want to see what method you're going to use today to wake everyone up. Secondly, the first squad to get up can have priority for breakfast," a soldier named Ravik replied. "You know how bad that breakfast is."
"You're right, Private Ravik," Kollen said. He reached out and pressed the switch. Suddenly, a shrill alarm rang out through the barracks. He heard people shouting loudly inside, accompanied by a commotion of hurried footsteps.
"Oh my God, Valturi," Nemici said. "I thought they would have already learned to get up with you by now."
"My brothers from basic training did," Kollen said, pointing at Harris, Cress, and Ravik. "But then again, their squad leaders and platoon leaders all knew to get up before their soldiers did."
A few seconds later, the rest of the soldiers from the platoon ran out. They were all dressed and ready. Some of the new recruits looked sleep-deprived, while others appeared very annoyed.
"Good morning, everyone," Kollen said cheerfully.
"With all due respect, sir, why did you wake us up in that way?" a突击队员 (corporal) asked.
"Because those ordinary alarm clocks are just trash. And Daybreak never sleeps in."
"Take your personal belongings," Kollen continued. As a lieutenant and deputy commander of the company, he had the responsibility to assist Captain Borodin Xiao, the company commander, in supervising and leading the company. "We won't be coming back. Sergeants and lieutenants, you and your troops have 15 minutes for a final check and to take today's rations with you."
The members of the Exodus company quickly dispersed. They were part of the 2nd Assault Division of the 2nd Army Group. Before the merger, they were originally two separate companies, Cohort and Dagger. It was an elite company, and Kollen felt a complex mix of emotions about his promotion to lieutenant, and there were many reasons for this.
Koren walked shoulder to shoulder with Nimitz, the first squad leader, along the brightly lit path of the base, where the lights on both sides were powered by generators. Most of the lights were red, which helped them avoid enemy bombers. In order to counter them, Daybreak had begun employing "Wildcat" tactics in both the air and on the ground.
"A new day, a new mission for the Hellbreakers," Nimitz said with a dry laugh. "Where are they going to send us this time?"
"Some frontline base outside the city of Ianlos. We've been sent to support the ground offensive," Koren said, taking a puff of his cigarette. He somewhat resented Cress for getting him hooked on cigarettes, but thinking back on the past year, they had gone through countless battles, so he let it go and said nothing.
"That's really bad. The frontline is under heavy pressure," Nimitz said quietly. "All the news coming from here is about 'supporting the war, aiding the Kurgan front,' why not support the Howlan front a bit?"
"Well said, brother," Koren said, flicking the cigarette butt into the mud. "We'll be going with the first armored squad, no walking involved. Captain Shaw should be there."
“Captain Xiao let us ride along?” Nimitch asked, somewhat surprised.
“Yes. To be honest, he isn't as bad as I imagined. I mean, he's not great, but he's not annoying either.”
Koren raised his thumb and index finger, pressing them against the microphone at his throat, while shifting his backpack to his back. “Exodus Company, all units, assemble at the West Yard after completing the mission. We will depart at 05:00 with the first armor platoon.”
Every few seconds, he received replies from the squad leaders. When they first arrived, Harris, Cress, and Ravick were junior sergeants. Since their basic training on Earth, the four of them had always been good friends. Koren felt like he had known them for a long time, even though it had been less than two years. They were all squad leaders, but since the previous platoon leader had been hit by a Daybreak sniper and retired due to injury a week ago, Cress had started leading the second platoon.
As they approached the vehicle yard, Koren and Nimitch's eyes fell upon about eight Chronos main battle tanks and four Stryker armored vehicles. Crew members were running around, ensuring their war machines were in good condition. Koren quickly spotted Captain Borodin Xiao in the crowd, who was talking with the armor platoon commander. As they approached, Captain Xiao looked at them and came forward, his usually cold face showing no emotion.
“Lieutenant Nimitz... Lieutenant Varturi...” he said, Colonel Kolen slowed his steps, Captain Shaw looked at Colonel Kolen's holster and then looked up. “Should the platoon be ready by now?”
